{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SF4XgvHbHPjhrn9pwLRvvx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about parsing/filtering logic — does the code correctly scope input to diff lines only? This is a logic question about how the code processes the diff. It's about one function's parsing logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed — you can construct a fake diff and verify the scoping logic.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If you mock the diff, you can still test whether the scoping logic correctly filters to changed lines.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: No — this is about what input is fed to the system, not what the LLM produces.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is Unit level — it's about parsing/filtering logic that can be tested with a constructed diff object.\n\n**Behavior 2: Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves mapping diff positions to GitHub's comment position API. The core question is whether the position mapping logic produces correct position numbers, though the failure mode emerges when that calculation interacts with the actual PR API.\n- REAL-INFRA: The \"diff view on the pull request\" implies you need the actual GitHub infrastructure to verify comments appear in the right place.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the GitHub API lets me verify the position numbers are correct, but I can't confirm GitHub interprets them properly in the UI.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThe position calculation itself can be unit-tested in isolation, but verifying it actually shows up correctly in GitHub's UI requires real HTTP calls. I'd classify this as Integration — the position mapping algorithm is testable at the unit level, but confirming the comment appears at the right place in the diff view requires testing against the real system.\n\nThe key question is whether mocking the GitHub API is sufficient. If I mock it, I can verify the correct position numbers are being sent, but I can't guarantee GitHub will render them correctly. However, the actual failure mode — sending the wrong position — can be caught without hitting real GitHub, so Integration testing with a mocked API should be enough to catch the real bugs.\n\nFor the agent identifying defects: this is explicitly about the LLM's ability to find bugs in a real pull request, which makes it LLM-dependent and Agentic.\n\nFor the summary-to-comments consistency check: this is about ensuring every finding in the top-level summary has a matching inline comment posted.  The tricky part is that if the LLM generates the summary separately from the inline comments, it might include extra findings that weren't actually commented on — so testing this properly requires checking whether the coordination logic actually enforces that constraint, not just mocking the LLM with deterministic outputs. The key distinction is whether the summary gets generated independently by the LLM or derived from the inline comments through code logic. If it's supposed to be aggregated deterministically from the inline findings, then this is an Integration test that verifies the coordination works correctly. If the LLM can hallucinate findings into the summary independently, that's an Agentic concern. I'll assume the former — the system should deterministically pull inline findings into the summary, so I'm testing that the aggregation logic works as intended.\n\nFor the full end-to-end sequence with a real pull request, this clearly involves actual GitHub API calls and a complete multi-step agent pipeline: reading the diff, using the LLM to identify issues, posting inline comments, then posting the summary. That's a Workflow-level test.\n\nSo my breakdown is: Unit for the scoping logic, Integration for position mapping and API coordination, Agentic for the LLM's bug detection quality, Integration again for consistency between inline and summary comments, and Workflow for the complete end-to-end pipeline. Now I need to assign probability weights to each level across all five behaviors.\n\nFor scoping to changed lines, the core logic is parsing, so Unit gets 0.75 with Integration at 0.20 for potential module interactions. Correct positions in the diff view is mostly Integration at 0.55 since I'd need to test the full pipeline with mocked API calls, though System gets 0.20 if real GitHub rendering matters. Identifying real defects is heavily Agentic at 0.83 since that requires the actual LLM to work properly.\n\nThe summary matching inline comments splits between Integration at 0.55 and Agentic at 0.20 if the LLM generates independently. The full sequence end-to-end is almost entirely Workflow at 0.74, since it depends on all the pieces working together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9549,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9549},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4166fecb-afa1-4ce0-9ca7-0a5f3872af8c","uuid":"b3e0f839-21df-4dbf-a19f-41a4773a189b"}
